1
00:00:05,126 --> 00:00:08,369
Foundation course in Buddhism, talk one.

2
00:00:09,330 --> 00:00:11,853
The first noble truth of suffering, dukkha.

3
00:00:13,275 --> 00:00:18,000
Dukkha literally means hard to bear or difficult to endure.

4
00:00:18,800 --> 00:00:30,172
So dukkha is variously translated as pain, suffering, misery, discontent, discomfort, unhappiness, frustration, unsatisfactoriness and such like.

5
00:00:30,946 --> 00:00:37,982
It is a very difficult word to translate into English, since it has so many shades of meaning, much as our word love has.

6
00:00:38,784 --> 00:00:44,838
But we need to know these meanings because dukkha is a central concept of the Buddha's teachings.

7
00:00:44,859 --> 00:00:47,706
In fact, it's the starting point of his whole doctrine.

8
00:00:48,731 --> 00:00:53,878
the first noble truth states that life itself is suffering, is unsatisfactory.

9
00:00:54,479 --> 00:01:01,609
Because of this bold statement, Buddhism is accused of being life-negating, of being negative and pessimistic.

10
00:01:02,331 --> 00:01:11,603
And it would be so, were it not for the third noble truth, which states in equally bold fashion that there is an end to suffering.

11
00:01:11,623 --> 00:01:16,730
The Buddha summed up his whole teaching saying that he only taught two things –

12
00:01:16,980 --> 00:01:19,384
the truth of suffering and the end of suffering.

13
00:01:20,686 --> 00:01:26,894
It was his experience of life as unsatisfactory that led the Buddha to leave home and follow the hard ascetic life.

14
00:01:28,117 --> 00:01:35,647
The Buddha was born into the Kshatriya caste, who were the rulers, governors, landed gentry, you might say, of those times.

15
00:01:36,757 --> 00:01:44,046
The other castes were, and still are in Hinduism, the Brahmins, the highest caste, who were the priests of the society.

16
00:01:44,768 --> 00:01:53,698
Beneath them the Kshatriya, then the Vaishya, who were the merchants and tradesmen, and finally the Sudra, who were the artisans and workers.

17
00:01:54,840 --> 00:01:58,864
All other peoples, such as the slaves, were outside the caste system.

18
00:01:59,566 --> 00:02:00,706
They were the pariahs.

19
00:02:01,597 --> 00:02:12,454
The Buddha's father was a leader of a small group of Kshatriya families known as the Sakyas, their clan name, who ruled in an area of North India on the border of present-day Nepal.

20
00:02:13,915 --> 00:02:21,447
Life for the young Siddhartha Gautama was, we can believe, easy and pleasant, and may even have been luxurious.

21
00:02:22,134 --> 00:02:31,645
It seems, however, that his courtly life upbringing did not hide from him the suffering inherent in life, and a legend tells how he came to face this.

22
00:02:32,606 --> 00:02:39,495
While out riding and hunting on various days, he first saw a sick man, then a dying man, and finally a corpse.

23
00:02:41,877 --> 00:02:45,901
Here is a passage from one of the discourses where the Buddha explains his experience.

24
00:02:46,902 --> 00:02:50,067
First he tells us how luxurious his life was.

25
00:02:50,586 --> 00:02:54,133
I was delicate, most delicate, extremely delicate.

26
00:02:54,875 --> 00:02:58,219
Lily pools were made at my father's house solely for my benefit.

27
00:02:58,822 --> 00:03:03,008
Blue lilies flowered one, white lilies another, red lilies a third.

28
00:03:03,770 --> 00:03:06,514
I used no sandalwood that was not of Benares.

29
00:03:07,096 --> 00:03:12,104
My turban, tunic, lower garments and cloak were all made of Benares cloth.

30
00:03:12,389 --> 00:03:20,725
A white sunshade was held over me day and night, so no cold, or heat, or dust, or grit, or dew might inconvenience me.

31
00:03:22,971 --> 00:03:31,207
So now we have an idea of his courtly lifestyle, but... Whilst I had such power and good fortune, yet I thought...

32
00:03:31,575 --> 00:03:44,354
When an ordinary untaught man who is subject to ageing, not safe from ageing, sees another who has aged, he is shocked, humiliated and disgusted, for he had forgotten that he himself is no exception.

33
00:03:45,194 --> 00:03:55,550
But I too am subject to ageing, not safe from ageing, and so it cannot be right for me to be shocked, humiliated and disgusted when I see another who has aged.

34
00:03:56,350 --> 00:04:00,317
When I considered this, the vanity of my youth completely left me.

35
00:04:01,512 --> 00:04:15,110
I thought, when an ordinary untaught man, who is subject to sickness, not safe from sickness, sees another who is sick, he is shocked, humiliated and disgusted, for he had forgotten that he himself is no exception.

36
00:04:15,790 --> 00:04:25,543
But I too am subject to sickness, not safe from sickness, and so it cannot be right for me to be shocked, humiliated and disgusted when I see another who is sick.

37
00:04:26,384 --> 00:04:30,810
When I considered this, the vanity of health completely left me.

38
00:04:32,072 --> 00:04:45,291
I thought, when an ordinary untaught man, who is subject to death, not safe from death, sees another who is dead, he is shocked, humiliated and disgusted, for he had forgotten that he himself is no exception.

39
00:04:46,112 --> 00:04:55,987
But I too am subject to death, not safe from death, so it cannot be right for me to be shocked, humiliated and disgusted when I see another who is dead.

40
00:04:57,189 --> 00:05:01,675
When I considered this, the vanity of life itself completely left me,

41
00:05:04,725 --> 00:05:17,605
Given the additions of an ordered tradition, for the scriptures were not actually written down for 500 years after the Buddha's death, what we can accept as fact is that the whole problem of suffering had become a major concern for the young nobleman.

42
00:05:18,646 --> 00:05:32,927
The last straw, it seems, was when he woke up in the early morning after a night of revelry, and saw about him bodies lying about in ungainly and disgusting positions, the air foul with the smell of alcohol and vomit.

43
00:05:33,211 --> 00:05:42,880
His sense of disgust, coupled with the growing weariness of trying to find any substantial or meaningful happiness in a life geared to sensual pleasure, finally caused him to leave.

44
00:05:44,862 --> 00:05:54,151
That early morning, he left on his favorite horse, Kanthaka, and with his faithful servant, Channa, rode beyond three kingdoms and crossed the river Anoma.

45
00:05:55,132 --> 00:06:00,298
He cut off his hair as a sign of renouncing the life devoted to sensual pleasure.

46
00:06:00,699 --> 00:06:05,047
He then gave his ornaments and jewellery to Channa and went in search of a teacher.

47
00:06:06,088 --> 00:06:10,536
It is said that such was the distress of his horse Khandaka that he died of a heart attack.

48
00:06:12,279 --> 00:06:22,557
In another discourse, reasons of a more philosophical nature are given by the Buddha to explain how he came to this momentous decision, known as the Great Renunciation.

49
00:06:23,887 --> 00:06:30,516
At this time, before I was enlightened, because I was subject to birth, I wanted to find out the nature of birth.

50
00:06:31,098 --> 00:06:40,994
So I thought to myself, since I am subject to birth, what if I were to find out what birth really is and discover the unsatisfactoriness of the nature of birth?

51
00:06:41,735 --> 00:06:45,822
So I set out to discover the unborn, the supreme of nibbana.

52
00:06:46,822 --> 00:06:49,927
And he says the same of sickness, old age and death.

53
00:06:50,144 --> 00:06:57,593
In other words, he left the court confident there was an end to suffering, which, by the way, was not annihilation.

54
00:06:59,857 --> 00:07:07,425
So what constitutes this dukkha, suffering or unsatisfactoriness, is divided into three categories.

55
00:07:07,867 --> 00:07:10,329
The first is called ordinary suffering.

56
00:07:10,833 --> 00:07:15,119
The second is called the suffering caused by the changing nature of life.

57
00:07:15,879 --> 00:07:20,005
And the third is that caused by our conditioning or conditioned states.

58
00:07:20,887 --> 00:07:25,834
Here we shall concern ourselves with the first category, ordinary suffering.

59
00:07:27,495 --> 00:07:38,190
This is how the Buddha expresses it in his first ever discourse after his enlightenment in which he expounds the basic teachings of the four noble truths and the eightfold noble path.

60
00:07:38,951 --> 00:07:40,113
It is called...

61
00:07:40,312 --> 00:07:43,177
the discourse on the turning of the wheel of the law.

62
00:07:44,940 --> 00:07:47,264
This is the first noble truth of suffering.

63
00:07:48,026 --> 00:07:49,387
Birth is suffering.

64
00:07:49,408 --> 00:07:51,031
Decay is suffering.

65
00:07:51,050 --> 00:07:51,971
Death is suffering.

66
00:07:52,572 --> 00:07:59,845
Sorrow, grief, lamentation, physical and mental pain, despair are all suffering.

67
00:07:59,865 --> 00:08:02,610
To be with what we dislike is suffering.

68
00:08:03,170 --> 00:08:06,456
To be separated from what we like is suffering.

69
00:08:07,819 --> 00:08:23,170
Here it is important to grasp that the Buddha is talking about those things people normally associate with suffering and pain, the whole birth process, teething, acne, hormonal changes, middle age crises, the aches and pains of growing old and the final agony of death.

70
00:08:24,333 --> 00:08:29,423
He also means the emotional pains of frustration, anxiety, depression, despair and so on.

71
00:08:30,144 --> 00:08:33,690
He is also saying that this is part and parcel of life itself.

72
00:08:34,211 --> 00:08:36,153
We are subject to this suffering.

73
00:08:36,173 --> 00:08:38,557
It's the package we receive when we're born.

74
00:08:40,759 --> 00:08:44,865
When we really contemplate this, really think about it, it's depressing.

75
00:08:45,527 --> 00:08:46,187
Yes, it's true.

76
00:08:47,389 --> 00:08:53,177
The only thing I can say with absolute certainty about my life is that it will end.

77
00:08:54,099 --> 00:08:56,322
I will die, whether I like it or not.

78
00:08:57,583 --> 00:09:08,475
But it is only when we find the courage to face this hard fact, rather than avoid it, that there can be any possibility of discovering if there is anything beyond this cycle of birth and death.

79
00:09:09,196 --> 00:09:11,077
That is what the Buddha did as a young man.

80
00:09:11,479 --> 00:09:18,346
He decided to face the facts, and it led him to discover that which is beyond birth and death, Nibbāna.

81
00:09:20,488 --> 00:09:26,595
Generally speaking, much of our suffering lies in the fact that we find it hard to face this sort of reality.

82
00:09:27,857 --> 00:09:34,972
It is a good exercise to look over the past and see how we have approached and tackled problems, upsets, catastrophes and traumas.

83
00:09:36,014 --> 00:09:40,684
One way we approach the painful is to avoid it, to shun it, to try and escape from it.

84
00:09:41,427 --> 00:09:45,174
We prefer to do anything but feel the pain, physical or mental.

85
00:09:45,610 --> 00:09:50,139
On a physical level, as soon as even a small ache is felt in the head, we reach for the bottle of pills.

86
00:09:50,841 --> 00:09:54,288
Sometimes, if we get a slight pain in the body, we'll ignore it.

87
00:09:54,830 --> 00:10:02,606
We'll pretend it's nothing, but underneath the apparent easy-going attitude is the fear we don't face that it may be a cancer or a dangerous illness.

88
00:10:03,092 --> 00:10:07,501
On the emotional level, if we feel depressed, we'll try and drown it out with a drink.

89
00:10:08,143 --> 00:10:10,989
If we feel bored, we'll try and escape by turning on the TV.

90
00:10:11,551 --> 00:10:13,595
If we feel lonely or anxious, we'll phone a friend.

91
00:10:14,076 --> 00:10:18,926
Anything not to feel the boredom, the depression, the anxiety, the loneliness and so on.

92
00:10:19,486 --> 00:10:21,311
We don't want to feel them.

93
00:10:21,331 --> 00:10:21,912
Why should we?

94
00:10:24,034 --> 00:10:32,113
If these escape routes are blocked, if we can't use our usual means of pushing these negative feelings away, we'll talk about them.

95
00:10:32,894 --> 00:10:40,129
We'll spend hours groaning, complaining, whinging and whining to family, friends, colleagues, doctors, anyone who'll listen.

96
00:10:40,630 --> 00:10:41,774
Even the cat gets an earful.

97
00:10:43,157 --> 00:10:43,798
For instance...

98
00:10:44,538 --> 00:10:47,162
Very few people will face up to the fact of death.

99
00:10:47,643 --> 00:10:50,687
You can joke about it, but you can't talk about it seriously.

100
00:10:51,087 --> 00:10:54,653
That can get too close to the feelings of terror and horror it arouses.

101
00:10:55,595 --> 00:10:57,778
Some will have long conversations about death.

102
00:10:58,318 --> 00:10:59,039
What is death?

103
00:10:59,220 --> 00:10:59,760
What is it?

104
00:10:59,821 --> 00:11:00,422
To die?

105
00:11:00,522 --> 00:11:02,225
To be or not to be?

106
00:11:02,664 --> 00:11:07,412
Wonderful questions, but all intellectualizations, all rationalizations.

107
00:11:08,474 --> 00:11:13,802
It makes you feel good to talk about and around death, but it's still escapism.

108
00:11:14,102 --> 00:11:15,605
It's just a mental exercise.

109
00:11:16,024 --> 00:11:20,490
It separates us from the real feelings we have about death.

110
00:11:20,510 --> 00:11:25,677
If we really want to know what it is to die, we should visit mortuaries and look upon actual corpses.

111
00:11:26,458 --> 00:11:29,984
Not for ghoulish fancies, but to arouse our subconscious fears.

112
00:11:30,924 --> 00:11:33,368
This is what the monks in the Buddha's time used to do.

113
00:11:33,908 --> 00:11:38,674
They would visit the charnel grounds and gaze upon dead bodies in different states of decay.

114
00:11:39,436 --> 00:11:41,038
Some do it even to this day, I believe.

115
00:11:42,418 --> 00:11:48,451
By such an exercise, we come to know not what death is, but rather how we relate to it.

116
00:11:49,494 --> 00:11:52,500
We can never know death as it really is till we actually die.

117
00:11:52,821 --> 00:11:54,544
So what's the point of talking about it?

118
00:11:55,447 --> 00:11:59,095
It's just another way of escaping our painful feelings, our suffering.

119
00:12:00,610 --> 00:12:15,652
The peculiar thing is that this sort of attitude, constantly turning away from what is painful, blocking it, rationalizing it, always escaping, causes the mind to dwell on the good side of life, the pleasures, the excitement, the bright future.

120
00:12:16,453 --> 00:12:18,736
It produces an unreal optimism.

121
00:12:19,274 --> 00:12:20,875
Things always turn out all right.

122
00:12:20,975 --> 00:12:21,856
Life's great.

123
00:12:22,177 --> 00:12:22,557
I'm happy.

124
00:12:23,099 --> 00:12:25,241
Eat, drink and be merry, for we die tomorrow.

125
00:12:25,601 --> 00:12:26,082
Not now.

126
00:12:26,943 --> 00:12:28,346
Anyway, it won't happen to me.

127
00:12:28,385 --> 00:12:29,988
Not in the foreseeable future.

128
00:12:30,489 --> 00:12:32,511
So what's all this talk about life is suffering?

129
00:12:32,552 --> 00:12:33,111
I'm happy.

130
00:12:33,533 --> 00:12:34,193
Life's great.

131
00:12:35,655 --> 00:12:40,221
This sort of optimism is obviously false, leading to false beliefs and false hopes.

132
00:12:40,822 --> 00:12:44,027
And beneath it all sits a lot of repressed fears and anxieties.

133
00:12:44,927 --> 00:12:48,673
Such a person is not prepared for the slings and arrows of outrageous fortune.

134
00:12:49,395 --> 00:12:58,283
When the Buddha states that life is unsatisfactory, he is asking us to see life as it really is, and not to shy away from its inbuilt suffering.

135
00:13:00,947 --> 00:13:06,432
The opposite of this approach to life is when we submit passively to suffering and misfortune.

136
00:13:07,351 --> 00:13:09,193
Life's hard, and then you die.

137
00:13:10,394 --> 00:13:13,077
A helplessness, a loss of reason for living.

138
00:13:13,597 --> 00:13:14,379
What's the point?

139
00:13:14,438 --> 00:13:16,660
It's all work, work, work.

140
00:13:16,681 --> 00:13:17,302
Why bother?

141
00:13:17,442 --> 00:13:18,863
We're all going to die.

142
00:13:19,383 --> 00:13:23,629
At first sight, compared to the optimist, this might seem a little more realistic.

143
00:13:24,250 --> 00:13:29,899
At least, the pessimist is accepting totally the one fact of life of which we can be certain.

144
00:13:30,662 --> 00:13:36,571
Indeed, in the face of overwhelming evidence that life does end, what is the point of effort, of success?

145
00:13:37,613 --> 00:13:39,956
Death mocks all our ambitions and achievements.

146
00:13:40,357 --> 00:13:51,410
The logical conclusion of such an understanding is despair and suicide, or a brave stoicism, where life just has to be suffered and you may as well make the best of a bad job.

147
00:13:52,913 --> 00:14:03,565
For such people, living can take on a certain desperation and sometimes, quite paradoxically, a compulsiveness to achieve, to win, to somehow fly in the face of despair.

148
00:14:05,705 --> 00:14:20,812
No doubt we've all faced certain events in our lives in these two ways to some degree or another, but is there another way of seeing life which neither leads us down the garden path of foolish hopes, nor drags us into tunnels of despair, despondency and gloom?

149
00:14:22,294 --> 00:14:30,109
The Buddha would have us investigate life impartially, to see it as it really is, accepting the situation totally.

150
00:14:30,476 --> 00:14:34,124
Within that clarity of view, it is easier for us to act.

151
00:14:34,706 --> 00:14:36,408
That is what he called the middle path.

152
00:14:37,652 --> 00:14:39,775
And it is often the name given to his teachings.

153
00:14:41,600 --> 00:14:43,644
His teachings were very clear on this point.

154
00:14:44,485 --> 00:14:51,539
Suffering is caused by seeking happiness in the pleasures of the senses because such things don't last.

155
00:14:52,432 --> 00:15:01,303
The person who concentrates his life on the next exciting thing to do is doing exactly this, forever seeking enjoyment, distraction and pleasure.

156
00:15:02,225 --> 00:15:04,889
Such persons are blind to the suffering that surrounds them.

157
00:15:06,150 --> 00:15:18,927
On the other hand, people who try to deny all pleasure and happiness and are overcome by the sufferings of life have become blinded to the possibility of the real peace and joy to be found in living.

158
00:15:20,191 --> 00:15:27,940
What is worse is that both are blinded to the higher reality that transcends both the pleasures and the tribulations of life.

159
00:15:28,902 --> 00:15:44,780
The Buddha asked us to take a realistic approach, not to pin our hopes on the transient pleasures of life, nor to be overcome by suffering and death, but to accept this dual situation totally, work within it, and try to discover what lies beyond it.

160
00:15:46,600 --> 00:15:50,865
This realistic approach can be experienced at first hand in our meditation.

161
00:15:51,947 --> 00:16:06,870
What is it we are doing but facing and accepting all the negativity that arises, observing all the pleasurable and joyful feelings and thoughts, and seeing all of this for what it really is, just passing phenomena, momentary mental objects.

162
00:16:07,794 --> 00:16:11,748
Realizing the passing nature of things undercuts false hopes.

163
00:16:12,551 --> 00:16:17,046
Seeing the arising of things, the birth of every moment, undercuts despair.

164
00:16:18,393 --> 00:16:20,956
Let us take the threat of nuclear war.

165
00:16:21,817 --> 00:16:26,365
Some people feel this threat of a nuclear holocaust as an ever-present reality.

166
00:16:27,025 --> 00:16:31,753
They are fearful and anxious, angry and frustrated, depressed and despairing.

167
00:16:32,534 --> 00:16:34,498
Others don't seem to see the danger at all.

168
00:16:35,119 --> 00:16:38,003
They feel secure under the nuclear umbrella, the deterrent.

169
00:16:38,683 --> 00:16:41,467
Anyway, they say, a nuclear war is unthinkable.

170
00:16:41,788 --> 00:16:42,951
What's the point of fighting it?

171
00:16:43,171 --> 00:16:43,851
No one would win.

172
00:16:44,432 --> 00:16:45,835
Humans wouldn't be so mad.

173
00:16:47,130 --> 00:16:54,182
Here, we have two opposite reactions to a given situation, the pessimistic and the falsely optimistic.

174
00:16:54,201 --> 00:17:06,000
Contemplating the possibility of a nuclear holocaust, even if it were to happen by mistake, might awaken those never-will-happen believers to the potential harm and motivate them to support disarmament.

175
00:17:06,637 --> 00:17:19,631
Accepting the possibility of nuclear holocaust with all that that means, especially to ourselves personally, for a lot of our fear of nuclear war is a fear of our own death, both fear and anxiety may be lessened.

176
00:17:20,632 --> 00:17:23,855
Once they are, we are much more capable of positive action.

177
00:17:24,675 --> 00:17:28,819
Anxiety and fear drain our energy, bring about panic and confusion.

178
00:17:29,701 --> 00:17:32,763
With a clearer mind, a more firm direction can be found.

179
00:17:33,284 --> 00:17:35,286
but we can only do what we can do.

180
00:17:36,208 --> 00:17:40,051
For some it may mean joining a march, for others influencing head of states.

181
00:17:40,752 --> 00:17:42,615
We have to accept our limitations.

182
00:17:43,316 --> 00:17:47,621
If we don't, we will suffer from anger, frustration, depression and despair.

183
00:17:48,481 --> 00:17:59,055
This polarity of pessimism and false optimism needs to be steadied towards a calm grasp of reality, seeing the situation just as it is.

184
00:17:59,525 --> 00:18:03,932
We need to be very much aware of how our emotions colour a situation.

185
00:18:06,557 --> 00:18:11,685
Here lies the importance of meditation practice, insight vipassana meditation.

186
00:18:13,087 --> 00:18:16,253
This was the Buddha's great discovery in his enlightenment.

187
00:18:16,273 --> 00:18:24,047
He discovered that by just developing awareness we are able to heal all our negativities and slowly purify the heart.

188
00:18:25,192 --> 00:18:31,902
When we sit, this is an opportunity to observe, really experience our moods and emotions, our states of mind.

189
00:18:33,084 --> 00:18:38,771
But investigate here does not mean to analyse, to ask questions, to wonder about the causes.

190
00:18:39,313 --> 00:18:45,040
It means simply to experience, to feel the emotions and mood as they really are.

191
00:18:46,021 --> 00:18:51,250
Equally important is to observe also our feelings about them, our reactions to them.

192
00:18:51,803 --> 00:18:54,586
When I feel depressed, how do I feel about it?

193
00:18:55,006 --> 00:18:55,747
Do I get angry?

194
00:18:56,327 --> 00:18:57,608
Do I get fearful and anxious?

195
00:18:57,969 --> 00:18:59,891
Do I get depressed about being depressed?

196
00:19:00,912 --> 00:19:07,219
The first step in the meditation is to begin to lose our fears and aversions towards states of mind.

197
00:19:08,279 --> 00:19:13,404
This is the first step in purifying the mind, having established some concentration on the breath.

198
00:19:14,205 --> 00:19:20,612
We observe any state of mind that arises, any mood or emotion that comes to our attention.

199
00:19:21,013 --> 00:19:22,816
Observe them as bodily feelings.

200
00:19:23,817 --> 00:19:30,204
There may be feelings of heaviness from depression, heat from anger, wobbliness from fear and tightness from anxiety.

201
00:19:30,746 --> 00:19:36,311
These feelings manifest in different parts of the body, sometimes in the chest or stomach or abdomen, for instance.

202
00:19:37,292 --> 00:19:41,097
We just watch it all calmly, noticing, observing.

203
00:19:41,999 --> 00:19:46,304
We see that everything is changing, everything is arising and passing away.

204
00:19:48,046 --> 00:19:49,468
What is it we are achieving here?

205
00:19:50,056 --> 00:19:57,590
By this simple observation, we are losing our fears of and aversions to negative states of mind as they arise.

206
00:19:58,593 --> 00:20:05,326
By not repressing these negative states of mind, they display themselves and to our amazement pass away.

207
00:20:06,007 --> 00:20:09,634
We are healing our hearts, we are purifying our minds.

208
00:20:11,301 --> 00:20:20,736
We must also be equally aware of pleasant feelings, observing them just as keenly, but this time observing how the mind grasps for them, longs to indulge in them.

209
00:20:21,317 --> 00:20:23,400
Of course, they pass away too.

210
00:20:24,421 --> 00:20:30,089
Observing the passing of pleasant states of mind stops us becoming falsely optimistic.

211
00:20:31,211 --> 00:20:37,140
Observing the passing of painful states of mind stops us becoming pessimistic.

212
00:20:37,373 --> 00:20:41,557
Seeing both as passing phenomena leads to a realistic view of life.

213
00:20:42,798 --> 00:20:48,765
When the mind is realistic, knowing things as they really are, it is equanimous and peaceful.

214
00:20:49,625 --> 00:20:54,590
To win a million or to lose a million does not ruffle this inner calm.

215
00:20:54,611 --> 00:20:56,553
This is the joy of the middle path.

216
00:20:57,513 --> 00:20:59,497
This is what the Buddha wanted us to do.

217
00:21:00,257 --> 00:21:02,740
To know ourselves as we really are.

218
00:21:02,955 --> 00:21:06,882
Meditation helps us to realize this, but it shouldn't stop there.

219
00:21:07,502 --> 00:21:12,349
We should keep this frame of mind, this understanding, throughout the day, every day.

220
00:21:16,496 --> 00:21:18,819
I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

221
00:21:21,163 --> 00:21:23,547
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

222
00:21:24,528 --> 00:21:27,613
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

